  "bib_entries": {
    "112785687": {
      "title": "Discussion on methods of de-icing for overhead transmission lines",
      "abstract": "It is an often-seen,natural phenomena that electric wires covered by ice at central china or alpine areas in winter and early-spring.Covering ice poses serious threat to the security of grid operation and costs millions of dollars in repair expenses.Power line icing is complicated phenomena,which involved thermodynamic and hydromechanical matters.Reduction of icedamage is a difficult problem,there are more than thirty kinds of measures are taken usually for resolve it.In general,they can be classed as two kinds: one is ice-melting by exterior or exterior heating of the overhead line,the other is through mechanical stripping of ice from conductors by equipments such as ice-rolling machines.This paper describes the mechanism of some innovative and practical methods for de-icing transmission lines such as reconfigure distribution network,short circuit,ice dielectric heating at high-frequency excitation and electromagnetic force on twin bundles and analyzed their merits and limitations.Furthermore,this paper introduces the achievement obtained in this field at home and abroad.This paper has been of great value to the security of power system."
    },
    "109811026": {
      "title": "The HQ LineROVer: contributing to innovation in transmission line maintenance",
      "abstract": "Innovations in transmission line maintenance have had a significant impact at many levels, including equipment reliability, continuity of service, inspection accuracy and efficiency, cost-effectiveness in maintenance practices, follow-up and safety. New live-line tools and methods will help utilities maintain the reliability of their aging transmission line installations in a challenging market. The HQ LineROVer was first presented as an overhead ground wire de-icing application in 2000 (ESMO conference). The prototype has since evolved into a third generation remotely operated vehicle (ROV). Many maintenance applications are now being targeted: visual and infrared inspection, evaluation of compression splice conditions (resistance measurements), replacement of conductors and ground wires (live), cleaning and de-icing of conductors. Live-line inspections have been realized on Hydro-Quebec's transmission network. Many other utilities throughout the world plan to use the ROV for their specific needs. The economic and strategic impacts of this new tool have been proven. Ongoing work on the HQ LineROVer and other ROVs will lead to the development of new live-line methods for transmission line maintenance."
    }
  },
